globalization,” but the author places it in its larger context: a five-thousand-year arms race, capitalism’s global reach, and the cultural effects of a worldwide communication network. Kelly predicts that the emergent phenomena of this fifth beginning will include the end of war as a viable way to resolve disputes, the end of capitalism as we know it, the widespread shift toward world citizenship, and the rise of forms of cooperation that will end the near-sacred status of nation-states. It’s the end of life as we have known it. However, the author is cautiously optimistic: he dwells not on the coming chaos, but on humanity’s great potential.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArchaeology. 0aCivilization. 0aCulture. 0aHuman beingsxHistory. 0aSocial history. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aactivist.  aagriculture.  aancient world.  aarchaeologist.  aarchaeology.  aarms race.  acapitalism.  acitizenship.  acommunication.  acultural history.  aculture.  aevidence.  afifth beginning.  aglobal.  aglobalization.  agovernment.  ahistory of culture.  ahistory.  ahuman development.  ahuman history.  ainternational.  alife changing.  along term.  amodern world.  anation states.  apolitics.  apotential.  asociety.  atechnology.  awartime.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029312040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096636940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966369423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966369/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY